ons of migrant Filipino women in maintaining families and communities, raising questions about gender relations, the status of women in globalization, and the meanings of greater consumptive power that migration garners for women. The Force of Domesticity starkly illustrates how the operation of globalization enforces notions of women’s domesticity and creates contradictory messages about women’s place in society, simultaneously pushing women inside and outside the home.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFilipino AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aForeign workers, Filipino. 0aWomen foreign workerszUnited States. 0aWomen household employeeszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh  aDocuments.  aadversities.  achildren.  acultural.  adomesticity.  amaintain.  amigrant.  amigration.  anegotiate.  apolitical.  apressures.  asocial.  athat.  atheir.  athese.  aways.  awell.  awomen.  awomens.1 aParreñas, Rhacel Salazar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTam, Winnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081476734440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814768556.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768556423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814768556/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  